His history has been compared to a drama, in which the story is presented entire, though the tediousness of continued narrationis avoided. He dedicated his labours to his friend and patron Robert earl of Gloucester, the natural son of King Henry the First. This eminent person appears to have possessed great legislative and military talents, and to have been much at- tached to literature. He seems to have acted only from the purest principles of justice and duty, without pride, passion, or selfish ambi- tion. Had he aspired to the throne when the nation had grown tired of Matilda and Ste- phen, he might possibly have gained it3 but he chose rather to preserve his fidelity and honour inviolate.
